Flexbox is a collection of CSS properties used to align content and distribute space

	Flexbox adds flex containers, flex items, and flexlines in addition to new properties
	NOTE the block of changing layout in flexbox is done by changing the properties of the parent elements.

			Current layout
		Block layout
		Table layout
		Inline layout
		Position layout

			Flex layout
		Flex containers
		Flex items
		Flex lines

	Flex containers control the layout of Child Items

		*HTML*

		<article class="setup">This . . . 
			<img height="150" height="150" . . .>
			<p> . . .</p>
		</article>		

		*CSS*

		article {
			border: 1px solid #d1eda6;
			display: flex
		}

	display: flex 
		Creates a Block-level Container which contains all available width.	

	display: inline-flex
		Creates an Inline Container

		*HTML*

		<article class="setup">This . . . 
			<img height="150" height="150" . . .>
			<p> . . .</p>
		</article>		

		*CSS*

		article {
			border: 1px solid #d1eda6;
			display: inline-flex
		}

	Flex Items are Distributed Along Flex Lines
		Flex Items are direct children of a flex container and can be HTML elements or text.
		A spacing algorithm is used to distributed space of all flex items across a single flex line.

				*HTML*

		<article class="setup">This . . . 
			<img height="150" height="150" . . .>
			<p> . . .</p>
		</article>		

		*CSS*

		article {
			border: 1px solid #d1eda6;
			display: inline-flex
		}

	Grouping Elements Into Flex Items:
		Grandchild elements do not become flex items.	
